-- CLOUD COMPUTING COURSE - RICH CONTENT
-- ============================================

UPDATE public.lessons SET
  content = E'# Introduction to Cloud Computing\n\n## What is Cloud Computing?\n\nCloud computing is the delivery of computing services—including servers, storage, databases, networking, software, analytics, and intelligence—over the Internet ("the cloud") to offer faster innovation, flexible resources, and economies of scale.\n\n## Key Characteristics\n\n1. **On-Demand Self-Service**: Provision resources automatically without human interaction\n2. **Broad Network Access**: Available over the network via standard mechanisms\n3. **Resource Pooling**: Provider resources serve multiple customers\n4. **Rapid Elasticity**: Scale up or down quickly\n5. **Measured Service**: Pay only for what you use\n\n## Benefits of Cloud Computing\n\n### Cost Savings\n- No upfront infrastructure costs\n- Pay-as-you-go pricing\n- Reduced IT staff needs\n- Lower energy costs\n\n### Scalability\n- Handle traffic spikes easily\n- Scale globally in minutes\n- Automatic resource allocation\n\n### Performance\n- Latest hardware and software\n- Global network of data centers\n- Reduced latency\n\n### Security\n- Enterprise-grade security\n- Compliance certifications\n- Regular security updates\n- Data encryption\n\n### Reliability\n- 99.9%+ uptime SLAs\n- Automatic backups\n- Disaster recovery\n- Redundancy\n\n## Cloud Deployment Models\n\n### Public Cloud\n- Owned by cloud provider\n- Shared infrastructure\n- Examples: AWS, Azure, Google Cloud\n- Best for: Startups, web applications\n\n### Private Cloud\n- Dedicated to single organization\n- On-premises or hosted\n- Greater control and security\n- Best for: Regulated industries, large enterprises\n\n### Hybrid Cloud\n- Combination of public and private\n- Data and applications shared between them\n- Flexibility and optimization\n- Best for: Organizations with varying workloads\n\n### Multi-Cloud\n- Using multiple cloud providers\n- Avoid vendor lock-in\n- Optimize costs and features\n- Best for: Large enterprises, specific requirements\n\n## Common Use Cases\n\n1. **Web Hosting**: Host websites and web applications\n2. **Data Storage**: Store and backup data\n3. **Development**: Build and test applications\n4. **Big Data Analytics**: Process large datasets\n5. **Machine Learning**: Train AI models\n6. **Disaster Recovery**: Backup and recovery solutions\n7. **IoT**: Connect and manage devices\n\n## Getting Started\n\n- Choose a cloud provider\n- Create a free tier account\n- Explore the console\n- Deploy your first application\n- Monitor usage and costs\n\n## Learning Path\n\n1. Understand cloud fundamentals\n2. Learn a major cloud platform (AWS, Azure, or GCP)\n3. Practice with hands-on labs\n4. Earn cloud certifications\n5. Build real-world projects',
  video_url = 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/M988_fsOSWo',
  duration_minutes = 25
WHERE title = 'Introduction to Cloud Computing';

UPDATE public.lessons SET
  content = E'# Cloud Service Models\n\n## Overview\n\nCloud computing offers three main service models, each providing different levels of control, flexibility, and management.\n\n## Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)\n\n### Definition\nProvides virtualized computing resources over the internet. You rent IT infrastructure—servers, VMs, storage, networks—from a cloud provider.\n\n### What You Manage\n- Operating systems\n- Applications\n- Data\n- Runtime\n- Middleware\n\n### What Provider Manages\n- Virtualization\n- Servers\n- Storage\n- Networking\n\n### Examples\n- Amazon EC2\n- Microsoft Azure VMs\n- Google Compute Engine\n- DigitalOcean Droplets\n\n### Use Cases\n- Website hosting\n- Development and testing\n- Storage and backup\n- High-performance computing\n\n### Advantages\n- Complete control\n- Highly scalable\n- Cost-effective\n- No hardware maintenance\n\n### Disadvantages\n- Requires technical expertise\n- Security responsibility\n- Management overhead\n\n## Platform as a Service (PaaS)\n\n### Definition\nProvides a platform allowing customers to develop, run, and manage applications without dealing with infrastructure.\n\n### What You Manage\n- Applications\n- Data\n\n### What Provider Manages\n- Runtime\n- Middleware\n- Operating system\n- Virtualization\n- Servers\n- Storage\n- Networking\n\n### Examples\n- Heroku\n- Google App Engine\n- AWS Elastic Beanstalk\n- Microsoft Azure App Service\n\n### Use Cases\n- Application development\n- API development\n- Business analytics\n- Database management\n\n### Advantages\n- Faster development\n- Reduced complexity\n- Built-in scalability\n- Integrated tools\n\n### Disadvantages\n- Less control\n- Potential vendor lock-in\n- Limited customization\n\n## Software as a Service (SaaS)\n\n### Definition\nDelivers software applications over the internet, on-demand and typically on a subscription basis.\n\n### What You Manage\n- Data\n- User access\n\n### What Provider Manages\n- Everything else (application, runtime, middleware, OS, infrastructure)\n\n### Examples\n- Google Workspace (Gmail, Docs)\n- Microsoft 365\n- Salesforce\n- Dropbox\n- Slack\n- Zoom\n\n### Use Cases\n- Email and collaboration\n- CRM\n- HR management\n- Accounting\n- Project management\n\n### Advantages\n- No installation needed\n- Accessible anywhere\n- Automatic updates\n- Lower upfront costs\n\n### Disadvantages\n- Limited customization\n- Data security concerns\n- Internet dependency\n- Subscription costs\n\n## Comparison Matrix\n\n| Feature | IaaS | PaaS | SaaS |\n|---------|------|------|------|\n| Control | High | Medium | Low |\n| Flexibility | High | Medium | Low |\n| Management | High | Medium | Low |\n| Technical Skill | High | Medium | Low |\n| Time to Deploy | Medium | Fast | Instant |\n| Cost | Variable | Medium | Predictable |\n\n## Choosing the Right Model\n\n### Choose IaaS if:\n- You need complete control\n- You have technical expertise\n- You want to migrate existing applications\n- You need custom configurations\n\n### Choose PaaS if:\n- You want to focus on development\n- You need rapid deployment\n- You want built-in scalability\n- You prefer managed infrastructure\n\n### Choose SaaS if:\n- You need quick implementation\n- You want minimal management\n- You need standard functionality\n- You prefer predictable costs\n\n## Emerging Models\n\n### Function as a Service (FaaS) / Serverless\n- AWS Lambda\n- Azure Functions\n- Google Cloud Functions\n- Event-driven execution\n- Pay per execution\n\n### Container as a Service (CaaS)\n- AWS ECS/EKS\n- Azure Container Instances\n- Google Kubernetes Engine\n- Container orchestration\n\n### Backend as a Service (BaaS)\n- Firebase\n- AWS Amplify\n- Supabase\n- Ready-made backend services\n\n## Best Practices\n\n1. Start with your requirements\n2. Consider your team''s skills\n3. Evaluate total cost of ownership\n4. Plan for scalability\n5. Consider security and compliance\n6. Test before committing\n7. Have an exit strategy',
  video_url = 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/36zducUX16w',
  duration_minutes = 35
WHERE title = 'Cloud Service Models';

UPDATE public.lessons SET
  content = E'# Major Cloud Providers\n\n## Overview\n\nThree major players dominate the cloud computing market: Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud Platform (GCP). Each offers unique strengths and services.\n\n## Amazon Web Services (AWS)\n\n### Market Position\n- **Market Share**: ~32% (largest provider)\n- **Launch Year**: 2006\n- **Data Centers**: 30+ regions, 90+ availability zones\n\n### Key Services\n- **Compute**: EC2, Lambda, ECS, EKS\n- **Storage**: S3, EBS, Glacier\n- **Database**: RDS, DynamoDB, Aurora\n- **Networking**: VPC, Route 53, CloudFront\n- **AI/ML**: SageMaker, Rekognition, Comprehend\n\n### Strengths\n- Largest service portfolio (200+ services)\n- Most mature platform\n- Extensive documentation\n- Large community\n- Global infrastructure\n\n### Best For\n- Startups and enterprises\n- Complex architectures\n- Global deployments\n- Innovation and experimentation\n\n### Pricing\n- Pay-as-you-go\n- Reserved instances (up to 75% savings)\n- Spot instances (up to 90% savings)\n- Free tier available\n\n### Certifications\n- AWS Certified Cloud Practitioner\n- AWS Certified Solutions Architect\n- AWS Certified Developer\n- AWS Certified SysOps Administrator\n\n## Microsoft Azure\n\n### Market Position\n- **Market Share**: ~20% (second largest)\n- **Launch Year**: 2010\n- **Data Centers**: 60+ regions\n\n### Key Services\n- **Compute**: Virtual Machines, App Service, Functions\n- **Storage**: Blob Storage, Files, Disks\n- **Database**: SQL Database, Cosmos DB\n- **Networking**: Virtual Network, Load Balancer, CDN\n- **AI/ML**: Machine Learning, Cognitive Services\n\n### Strengths\n- Best Microsoft integration\n- Hybrid cloud capabilities\n- Enterprise focus\n- Active Directory integration\n- Strong compliance offerings\n\n### Best For\n- Microsoft-centric organizations\n- Hybrid cloud scenarios\n- Enterprise applications\n- .NET applications\n\n### Pricing\n- Pay-as-you-go\n- Reserved instances\n- Azure Hybrid Benefit\n- Free tier and credits\n\n### Certifications\n- Azure Fundamentals\n- Azure Administrator\n- Azure Developer\n- Azure Solutions Architect\n\n## Google Cloud Platform (GCP)\n\n### Market Position\n- **Market Share**: ~10% (third largest)\n- **Launch Year**: 2008\n- **Data Centers**: 35+ regions\n\n### Key Services\n- **Compute**: Compute Engine, App Engine, Cloud Functions\n- **Storage**: Cloud Storage, Persistent Disks\n- **Database**: Cloud SQL, Firestore, Bigtable\n- **Networking**: VPC, Cloud Load Balancing, Cloud CDN\n- **AI/ML**: Vertex AI, AutoML, TensorFlow\n\n### Strengths\n- Best for data analytics and ML\n- Kubernetes expertise (created K8s)\n- Competitive pricing\n- Strong network infrastructure\n- Innovation focus\n\n### Best For\n- Data-intensive applications\n- Machine learning projects\n- Container-based applications\n- Startups and developers\n\n### Pricing\n- Pay-as-you-go\n- Sustained use discounts (automatic)\n- Committed use discounts\n- Free tier available\n\n### Certifications\n- Cloud Digital Leader\n- Associate Cloud Engineer\n- Professional Cloud Architect\n- Professional Data Engineer\n\n## Other Notable Providers\n\n### IBM Cloud\n- Strong in enterprise and hybrid\n- Watson AI services\n- Quantum computing\n\n### Oracle Cloud\n- Database-focused\n- Enterprise applications\n- Autonomous services\n\n### Alibaba Cloud\n- Leading in Asia\n- E-commerce expertise\n- Growing globally\n\n### DigitalOcean\n- Developer-friendly\n- Simple pricing\n- Great for small projects\n\n## Comparison Matrix\n\n| Feature | AWS | Azure | GCP |\n|---------|-----|-------|-----|\n| Market Share | 32% | 20% | 10% |\n| Services | 200+ | 200+ | 100+ |\n| Regions | 30+ | 60+ | 35+ |\n| Pricing | Complex | Moderate | Simple |\n| Learning Curve | Steep | Moderate | Moderate |\n| Best For | Everything | Enterprise | Data/ML |\n\n## Choosing a Provider\n\n### Consider:\n1. **Existing Infrastructure**: What are you currently using?\n2. **Technical Requirements**: What services do you need?\n3. **Team Skills**: What does your team know?\n4. **Budget**: What can you afford?\n5. **Compliance**: What regulations apply?\n6. **Geographic Needs**: Where are your users?\n7. **Support**: What level of support do you need?\n\n### Decision Framework\n\n**Choose AWS if:**\n- You need the most services\n- You want the largest community\n- You''re building complex systems\n- You need global reach\n\n**Choose Azure if:**\n- You use Microsoft products\n- You need hybrid cloud\n- You''re an enterprise\n- You need strong compliance\n\n**Choose GCP if:**\n- You focus on data/ML\n- You use containers heavily\n- You want simple pricing\n- You value innovation\n\n## Multi-Cloud Strategy\n\nMany organizations use multiple providers:\n- **Avoid vendor lock-in**\n- **Optimize costs**\n- **Use best-of-breed services**\n- **Meet compliance requirements**\n- **Improve reliability**\n\n### Challenges\n- Increased complexity\n- Higher management overhead\n- Need for multi-cloud expertise\n- Integration difficulties\n\n## Getting Started\n\n1. **Create free accounts** on all three platforms\n2. **Complete tutorials** for each\n3. **Build the same project** on each platform\n4. **Compare experiences** and costs\n5. **Choose based on your needs**\n\n## Resources\n\n- **AWS**: aws.amazon.com/training\n- **Azure**: learn.microsoft.com\n- **GCP**: cloud.google.com/training\n- **Comparison Tools**: CloudOrado, CloudHarmony\n- **Communities**: Reddit, Stack Overflow, Discord',
  video_url = 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/SXB4IHkU7Wk',
  duration_minutes = 40
WHERE title = 'Major Cloud Providers';

